sections.example:
Let's create a simple functional component called Greeting. This component will accept a prop called 'name' and display a greeting message. Here’s how it looks:

function Greeting(props) {
  return <h1>Hello, {props.name}!</h1>;
}

In this example, 'Greeting' is a function that takes 'props' as an argument. Inside the function, we return a JSX element, which is an <h1> tag that displays 'Hello,' followed by the value of 'props.name'. When you use this component in your app, you can pass different names to it, like this:

<Greeting name='Alice' />

This will render 'Hello, Alice!'. If you use <Greeting name='Bob' />, it will render 'Hello, Bob!'. This demonstrates how components can be reused with different data.

Let’s enhance our previous example by creating a parent component that uses the Greeting component. Here’s how it looks:

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Greeting name='Alice' />
      <Greeting name='Bob' />
    </div>
  );
}

In this example, 'App' is the parent component that renders two instances of the 'Greeting' component. Each instance receives a different name prop. When you run this code, it will display:

Hello, Alice!
Hello, Bob!

This shows how props allow you to pass different data to the same component, making it reusable and dynamic.
